{"title_page": "Foreign hostages in Iraq", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{cleanup reorganize|date=June 2017}}\n{{confusing|date=June 2017}}\n{{prose|date=June 2017}}\n{{update|date=June 2017}}\n{{citation style|date=September 2014}}\n}}\n\nMembers of the [[Iraqi insurgency (Iraq War)|Iraqi insurgency]] began taking '''foreign hostages in Iraq''' beginning in April 2004. Since then, in a dramatic instance of Islamist kidnapping they have taken captive more than 200 foreigners and thousands of [[Iraqis]]; among them, dozens of hostages were killed and others rescued or freed. In 2004, executions of captives were often filmed, and many were [[decapitation|beheaded]].<ref name=\"SRB Nov 30\">{{cite news|last=Mathewson|first=Judy|title=U.S. Christian Group Names Captives in Iraq, Blames U.S., U.K.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=apjiZ3TwohoI|publisher=Bloomberg News|accessdate=April 24, 2013|date=November 30, 2005<!-- 11:24 EST-->}}</ref> However, the number of the recorded killings decreased significantly. Many hostages remain missing with no clue as to their whereabouts. The [[United States Department of State]] [[Hostage Working Group]] was organized by the [[U.S. Embassy, Baghdad]], in the summer of 2004 to monitor foreign hostages in Iraq.\n\nThe motives for these kidnappings include:\n* influencing foreign governments with troops in Iraq to withdraw\n* influencing foreign companies with workers in Iraq to leave the country\n* [[ransom]] money\n* discouraging travel to Iraq\n* [[prisoner exchange]]\n\nThe following is a list of known civilian foreign hostages in Iraq.\n{{TOC right|limit=4}}\n\n== Coalition ==\n\n=== Australia ===\n==== 2 Released/Rescued ====\n:* [[John Martinkus]], a journalist for [[SBS Television]], was kidnapped on October 16, 2004. He was released on October 18, 2004, after his captors used [[Google]] to verify his status as a journalist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newmatilda.com/print/629 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115052813/http://newmatilda.com/print/629 |archivedate=2010-01-15 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/3755154.stm | work=BBC News | title=Google 'saved' Australian hostage | date=October 19, 2004 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n:* [[Douglas Wood (engineer)|Douglas Wood]], construction engineer was kidnapped along with two Iraqi business associates on April 30, 2005. The two associates were later killed. Wood was rescued on June 15, 2005 in a raid carried out by the [[Iraqi Army]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/iraqi-family-gets-no-answer-to-asylum-plea/2006/05/28/1148754871340.html | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=Iraqi family gets no answer to asylum plea | date=May 29, 2006 | first=Sarah | last=Smiles}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200506/s1393071.htm |title=ABC.net.au |access-date=2009-11-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515212045/http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200506/s1393071.htm |archive-date=2008-05-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Bulgaria ===\n==== 2 Killed ====\n:* Georgi Lazov and Ivailo Kepov, two truck drivers, were seized on June 29, 2004, near [[Mosul]]. Lazov's beheaded body was found on July 14, 2004; Kepov's on July 22, 2004.<ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-07/23/content_351092.htm Body discovery stokes Iraq hostage tension] ''China Daily'', 2004-07-23</ref>\n\n=== Czech Republic ===\n==== 3 Released ====\n:* Reporter Michal Kubal and cameraman Petr Kl\u00edma, of [[\u010cesk\u00e1 televize|Czech television]] and V\u00edt Pohanka from [[\u010cesk\u00fd rozhlas|Czech Radio]] were kidnapped on April 11, 2004. They were freed April 16, 2004.<ref name=cpj>{{cite web|url=http://cpj.org/reports/2008/04/abducted.php|title=Iraq: Journalists Abducted 2003-09|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Denmark ===\n==== 1 Killed ====\n:* Henrik Frandsen was abducted on April 11, 2004, while working on a sewage project, and found dead the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.breakingnews.ie/archives/2004/0421/world/body-of-missing-dane-found-in-iraq-143819.html|title=Body of missing Dane found in Iraq|work=Breaking News|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Italy ===\n==== 4 Killed ====\n:* [[Fabrizio Quattrocchi]], a security guard captured with three others, was reported killed in a video released on April 14, 2004.\n:* [[Enzo Baldoni]], a reporter taken hostage in August and shown being killed in a video released on August 26, 2004. His Iraqi driver-translator was killed during the abduction.\n:* Salvatore Santoro, a photojournalist, reported kidnapped and killed on December 16, 2004.\n:* Iyad Anwar Wali, an Italian-Iraqi businessman, was reported killed on October 2, 2004.\n\n==== 6 Released ====\n:*Umberto Cupertino, Maurizio Agliana and Salvatore Stefio were captured with security guard Fabrizio Quattrocchi on April 29, 2004. The three were freed June 8, 2004.<ref name=smh>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/06/09/1086460306101.html|title=Iraqi hostages freed 'without bloodshed'|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n:*Simona Pari and Simona Torretta, aid workers for a Bridge to Baghdad, were kidnapped along with two Iraqis on September 7, 2004. They were freed on September 28, 2004. Italy allegedly paid $5 million in ransom for their release.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/iraq/article723364.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=How 45m secretly bought freedom of foreign hostages | first=Daniel | last=McGrory | date=May 22, 2006 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n:*[[Giuliana Sgrena]], a reporter for ''Il Manifesto'', was kidnapped on February 4, 2005. Her Iraqi driver and Iraqi translator managed to escape. When she was released on March 4, 2005, her car was shot at by US troops, and Italian agent [[Nicola Calipari]] was killed. Italy allegedly paid $6 million in ransom for her release.\n\n=== Japan ===\n==== 2 Killed ====\n:* [[Shosei Koda]], a tourist, was confirmed beheaded on October 30, 2004. He had been kidnapped on October 26, 2004 by Zarqawi's group.\n:* [[Akihiko Saito]], a security contractor, was kidnapped after a convoy attack and reported killed on May 28, 2005.\n\n==== 3 Released ====\n:* Soichiro Koriyama, Noriaki Imai, and Nahoko Takato, Japanese citizens were kidnapped on April 8, 2004, but released on April 15, 2004.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/panorama/4627777.stm Noriaki Imai profile] BBC</ref>\n\n=== Macedonia ===\n==== 3 Killed ====\n:* Dalibor Lazarevski, Dragan Markovi\u0107, and Zoran Naskovski, were kidnapped August 21, 2004, near Baghdad. They worked for Soufan Engineering, which caters to the needs of the US military and its private contractors. On October 22, 2004, the Macedonian government confirmed the three had been killed.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/3944711.stm Macedonian Iraq hostages killed] BBC, 22 October 2004.</ref>\n\n==== 2 Released ====\n:* Faruk Ademi and Rasim Ramadani, two contractors working for a cleaning company at [[Basra International Airport]] were abducted on February 16, 2006. They were released on February 20, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.osservatoriobalcani.org/article/articleview/9488/1/407|title=Home - Osservatorio Balcani e Caucaso |author=Osservatorio Balcani e Caucaso|work=[[Osservatorio Balcani e Caucaso]]|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== The Philippines ===\n==== 2 Released ====\n:* Angelo de la Cruz, a truck driver, was taken hostage on July 7, 2004. De la Cruz was released after the Philippines withdrew their 51 troops in the country on July 20, 2004. His Iraqi security guard was killed during the abduction.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200407/s1158208.htm Embassy confirms Filipino hostage's release] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050326182212/http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200407/s1158208.htm |date=2005-03-26 }} ABC News Online.</ref>\n:* Roberto Tarongoy, kidnapped on November 1, 2004. He was released eight months later, on June 22, 2005 after a ransom was paid.<ref>[http://edition.cnn.com/2005/WORLD/asiapcf/06/22/iraq.philippines/index.html Iraq hostage free after 7 months] CNN.</ref>\n\n=== Poland ===\n==== 2 Released ====\n:* Jerzy Kos, a contractor kidnapped on June 1, 2004, was freed in an operation on June 8, 2004.<ref name=smh/>\n:* Teresa Borcz Khalifa, a Polish aid worker, was kidnapped on October 28, 2004. She was freed on November 20, 2004.\n\n=== Romania ===\n==== 3 Released ====\n:* Marie Jeanne Ion, Sorin Dumitru Miscoci, and Ovidiu Ohanesian, journalists, were kidnapped on March 28, 2005 in Baghdad. Their Iraqi-American translator, [[Mohammad Munaf]], also went missing with them. They were released on May 22, 2005. Munaf was accused by the Romanian government of organizing the kidnapping and was arrested.<ref name=cpj/><ref>[https://archive.today/20120910021300/http://www.romaniantimes.at/news/General_News/2009-09-22/3042/Munaf%92s_ten-year_prison_sentence_is_final_ Munaf's ten year prison sentence is final] ''Romanian Times''.</ref>\n\n=== South Korea ===\n==== 1 Killed ====\n:* [[Kim Sun-il]], a translator, was kidnapped on May 30, 2004 by Zarqawi's group. He was beheaded in a video released June 22, 2004.\n\n=== Ukraine ===\n==== 5 Released ====\n:* Five energy workers from Interenergoservis were kidnapped on April 12, 2004, along with 3 Russians and a man immediately released, all were released the next day with the insurgents apologizing, noting that they did not realise they were Russian and Ukrainian.<ref name=\"indolink.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indolink.com/printArticleS.php?id=041304055115|title=INDOlink - Indian Diaspora (NRI) News - Russian, Ukrainian Hostages In Iraq Freed|accessdate=29 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303174651/http://www.indolink.com/printArticleS.php?id=041304055115|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\n==== 5 Killed ====\n:* [[Kenneth Bigley|Kenneth John Bigley]], a civil engineer, who was kidnapped September 16, 2004. The two Americans kidnapped with him were beheaded and Bigley was beheaded around October 7.\n:* Jason Swindlehurst, Jason Creswell, Alec Maclachlan and Alan McMenemy, four security contractors, were kidnapped with Peter Moore, a computer consultant, on May 29, 2007. Their captors were Shia militiamen who demanded the withdrawal of British troops from Iraq and release of all Iraqi prisoners in exchange for the hostages's release. Creswell, McMenemy and Moore appeared in videos released in November 2007, February 2008 and July 2008. The captors claimed that Swindlehurst killed himself on May 25, 2008. However, that turned out to be a lie. The bodies of Swindlehurst and Creswell were recovered on June 19, 2009. On July 29, 2009, it was revealed that Maclachlan and McMenemy had also been killed. Maclachlan's body was recovered on September 1, 2009. McMenemy's body was recovered on January 20, 2012.<ref>{{cite news | first1=Sean | last1=Rayment | first2=Damien | last2=McElroy |title=British hostages in Iraq named after bodies found|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iraq/5594701/British-hostages-in-Iraq-named-after-bodies-found.html | publisher = Daily Telegraph | location=London | date=June 21, 2009 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"khaleejtimes.com\">[http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticleNew.asp?col=&section=middleeast&xfile=data/middleeast/2009/July/middleeast_July705.xml Khaleejtimes.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608213422/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticleNew.asp?col=&section=middleeast&xfile=data%2Fmiddleeast%2F2009%2FJuly%2Fmiddleeast_July705.xml |date=2011-06-08 }}</ref><ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\">{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/iraq/article6820635.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=End the torment says Brown as death of British hostage is confirmed | first=Oliver | last=August | date=September 4, 2009 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc16660750\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16660750 | work=BBC | title= Body of Iraq kidnap victim Alan McMenemy handed over | date=January 20, 2012 | accessdate=January 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==== 6 Released ====\n:* Gary Teeley, a laundry contractor at an American base outside [[Nasiriyah]], was kidnapped on April 5, 2004. He was freed by his kidnappers on April 11, 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?art_id=qw1081751040494B262|title=Violence rages on in Fallujah despite truce|author=Independent Newspapers Online|work=Independent Online|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n:* [[James Brandon (journalist)|James Brandon]], a freelance journalist for ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'', was kidnapped after 30 masked gunmen stormed into his hotel in [[Basra]] on August 12, 2004. He was freed on August 13, 2004, by his captors.<ref name=cpj/>\n:* Phillip Sands, a freelancer reporter, was abducted on December 26, 2005, along with his Iraqi interpreter and Iraqi driver. His abductors were gunmen who planned on using him to get Britain to pull all troops out of Iraq and release all Iraqi prisoners. Phillip was filmed pleading for his life. However, the tape was never sent to Al Jazeera. On December 31, 2005, Phillip and his two colleagues were rescued by U.S. troops who revealed that no one knew they were missing.<ref name=cpj/>\n:* [[Norman Kember|Norman Frank Kember]], an aid worker for Christian Peacemaker Teams, was kidnapped along with two Canadians and an American on November 27, 2005. Their Iraqi driver and Iraqi translator were not taken.<ref name=\"SRB Nov 30\"/> He was released as the result of a Coalition operation on March 23, 2006. See [[2005-2006 Christian Peacemaker hostage crisis]].\n:* Richard Butler, a journalist working for [[CBS News]], was kidnapped in Basra on February 10, 2008, with his Iraqi interpreter Aqeel Khadhir. The translator was freed on February 13, 2008. Butler was rescued on April 14, 2008 by Iraqi forces.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/15/world/middleeast/15iraq.html | work=The New York Times | title=Two Journalists Are Released in Iraq | first1=Erica | last1=Goode | first2=Qais | last2=Mizher | date=April 15, 2008 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Kidnapped CBS Journalist Freed In Iraq |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/kidnapped-cbs-journalist-freed-in-iraq/ |date= 14 April 2008 |publisher= cbsnews |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:* Peter Moore, a computer consultant, and his four security guards were kidnapped from the Iraqi Finance ministry on May 29, 2007.<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/dec/30/iran-britons-baghdad-kidnapping | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Revealed: hand of Iran behind Britons' Baghdad kidnapping | first=Guy | last=Grandjean | date=December 30, 2009 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref> Peter and two of his security guards appeared in videos released in November 2007, February 2008 and July 2008. Their captors were Shia militiamen who demanded the withdrawal of British troops from Iraq and the release of all Iraqi prisoners in exchange for the hostages's release. Their captors claimed that Swindlehurst killed himself on May 25, 2008. However that turned out to be a lie. The bodies of Swindlehurst and Creswell were recovered on June 19, 2009. Both of them were shot dead. On July 29, 2009, it was revealed that Maclachlan and McMenemy were also killed. The body of Maclachlan was recovered on September 1, 2009. He was also shot dead. McMenemy's body was recovered on January 20, 2012.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iraq/5594701/British-hostages-in-Iraq-named-after-bodies-found.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | title=British hostages in Iraq named after bodies found Two British men, Jason Creswell and Jason Swindlehurst, have been named by the Foreign Office as \"highly likely\" to have been killed, after being kidnapped and held hostage in Iraq since 2007 | first1=Sean | last1=Rayment | first2=Damien | last2=McElroy | date=June 21, 2009 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"khaleejtimes.com\"/><ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"bbc16660750\"/> Moore was released on December 30, 2009 in exchange for the release of [[Qais Khazali]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8435075.stm | work=BBC News | title=UK hostage released alive in Iraq | date=December 30, 2009 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref> In December 2009 evidence uncovered during an investigation by the Guardian newspaper and Guardian Films linked the [[Quds Force]] to the kidnappings of Moore, Swindlehurst, Maclachlan, Creswell and McMenemy.<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\"/>\n\n=== United States ===\n====11 Killed====\n:* [[Nick Berg|Nicholas Evan Berg]], a 26 year old freelancer, went missing on 9 April 2004. His widely publicized beheading was shown in a video on 11 May 2004. His body had been found the day before. [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]] personally beheaded Berg.<ref>''[[Die Welt]] '', 20 November 2014.</ref>\n:* Owen Eugene \"Jack\" Armstrong and Jack Hensley, two contractors for the [[construction]] firm ''Gulf Supplies Commercial Services'' of the [[United Arab Emirates]],<ref name=\"employer\">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/09/20/iraq.beheading/|title=Video shows American hostage beheaded|accessdate=30 March 2008|publisher=CNN|date=20 September 2004}}</ref> were kidnapped along with a Briton named [[Kenneth Bigley|Kenneth John Bigley]] on September 16, 2004. Armstrong was [[decapitation|beheaded]]<ref name=factbox>[https://www.reuters.com/article/topNews/idUSL297059220070531 FACTBOX-Prominent kidnappings of foreigners in Iraq] Accessed 12 March 2008.</ref> on 20 September 2004.<ref name=\"captors\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/american-hostage-beheaded-video-1.473228|title=American hostage beheaded: video|accessdate=2008-03-30|publisher=CBC|date=20 September 2004}}</ref> Abu Musab al-Zarqawi personally beheaded Armstrong.<ref>Romans, Christine and Rhonda Schaffler. \"[http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-13436508_ITM American Beheaded in Iraq; Dates for Presidential Debates to be Set; Dan Rather Apologizes for Bush Story - Part 1]\", accessmylibrary.com, 20 September 2004; retrieved 9 March 2011.</ref> The following day, the group beheaded Hensley, and threatened to kill Bigley, unless the [[United States]] met their demands to free all women prisoners in Iraqi jails.<ref name=\"employer\"/> Bigley was beheaded in October 2004.<ref name=factbox/>\n:* [[Ronald Alan Schulz]], an electrician, was reported kidnapped on 6 December 2005. On 19 December 2005, the Islamic Army released a video showing Schulz's killing in which he is shot in the head after the U.S. refused to release all Iraqi prisoners. His remains were found in September 2008 and confirmed to be Schulz's the next month.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081030/ap_on_re_us/iraq_hostage_burial_1 Re killing of Ronald Schulz], News.yahoo.com; accessed 16 September 2015.</ref>\n:* [[Tom Fox (activist)|Thomas William Fox]], an aid worker working for [[Christian Peacemaker Teams]], was reported kidnapped on November 27, 2005, along with two Canadians and a Briton. Their Iraqi driver and Iraqi translator were not taken.<ref name=\"SRB Nov 30\"/> His body was found in a rubbish heap on 10 March 2006 (see [[2005-2006 Christian Peacemaker hostage crisis]]).\n:*John Roy Young, Joshua Mark Munns, Paul Christopher Reuben and Jonathon Michael Cote, four security contractors, were kidnapped with an Austrian named Bert Nussbaumer on November 16, 2006. They appeared in two hostage videos released in December 2006 and January 2007. The kidnapped contractors stated in their video that they would not be released until the following demands had been made; the withdrawal of American troops from Iraq and the release of all Iraqi prisoners in exchange for the hostages's release. Four fingers were sent to U.S. authorities in February 2008. The fingers belonged to Munns, Reuben, Cote and Nussbaumer. The bodies of Young, Nussbaumer, Munns and Reuben were recovered in March 2008. Cote's body was recovered in April 2008.<ref name=\"buffalonews.com\">[http://www.buffalonews.com/cityregion/story/477265.html Buffalonews.com]</ref><ref>[http://www.buffalonews.com/cityregion/buffaloerie/story/331348.html Buffalonews.com]</ref>\n:*Ronald Withrow, a contractor, was kidnapped along with his translator and driver on 5 January 2007. The translator and driver were found dead the next day. One of Withrow's fingers was sent to U.S. authorities in February 2008. His body was recovered in March 2008.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/28/world/middleeast/28bodies.html 2 More Bodies ID'd as Kidnapped Contractors], nytimes.com; 28 March 2008.</ref>\n:*[[Steven Vincent|Steven Charles Vincent]], a journalist, was kidnapped along with his Iraqi translator, Nouriya Itais Wadi, in Basra on 2 August 2005. They were bound, gagged, taken to an undisclosed location where for five hours they were beaten and interrogated, then taken to the outskirts of town and shot. They were found by British and Iraqi policemen but Vincent was dead, shot in the back at close range. Wadi survived despite having been shot three times.<ref name=cpj/>\n\n==== 6 Released/Escaped ====\n:* [[Jill Carroll]], a freelance reporter for the Boston-based ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'', was kidnapped in West Baghdad on January 7, 2006, by unknown gunmen. Her Iraqi translator was killed during the abduction. Her Iraqi driver escaped. Her kidnappers demanded the release of all female Iraqi prisoners. She was shown in four videos during her captivity. She was released on March 30, 2006.\n:* [[Micah Garen]], a freelance reporter, was kidnapped along with his Iraqi translator, Amir Doushi, on August 13, 2004, near [[Nasiriyah]]. They were freed on August 22, 2004.<ref name=cpj/>\n:* [[Roy Hallums]], an employee of a Saudi trading company, was seized along with Roberto Tarangoy, Inus Dewari and three Iraqi security guards on November 1, 2004, in Baghdad. The three Iraqi security guards were later released. Dewari was released on November 10, 2004. Hallums was shown in a video aired on January 25, 2005. Tarongoy was released on June 22, 2005. On September 7, 2005, Hallums was freed in an operation conducted by [[Delta Force]].\n:* Thomas Hamill, a truck driver, was seized in a deadly convoy attack on April 9, 2004 (see [[2004 Iraq KBR Convoy Ambush]]). He was later shown in a video, but escaped on May 1, 2004.<ref>\"[http://edition.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/02/iraq.main/index.html Kidnapped U.S. contractor found safe]\". May 2, 2004, CNN.</ref>\n:* Issa T. Salomi, a civilian contractor, was kidnapped by a Shiite militia group on January 23, 2010, and shown in a video in February 2010. His kidnappers demanded the release of Iraqi prisoners, the withdrawal of all foreign troops from Iraq, the prosecution of security contractors employed by [[Blackwater Worldwide]] and compensation to Iraqi families. He was released on March 25, 2010 in exchange for the release of four Iraqi prisoners.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/02/06/AR2010020601062.html | work=The Washington Post | first1=Ernesto | last1=Londo\u00f1o | first2=Leila | last2=Fadel | title=American contractor kidnapped in Iraq | date=February 6, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/id/36067041|title=Contractor found in Iraq; family rejoices - World news - Mideast/N. Africa - Conflict in Iraq - NBC News|work=NBC News|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n:* [[Paul Taggart]], a freelance photographer, was kidnapped on October 10, 2004. He was released on October 12, 2004.<ref name=cpj/>\n\n==== 5 Unknown ====\n:* [[Kirk von Ackermann]], contractor for a Turkish company, disappeared on October 9, 2003 after leaving a meeting at FOB Pacesetter. His vehicle was found abandoned later that same day.\n:* Timothy Edward Bell, a contractor for [[Halliburton]], went missing on April 9, 2004. He was never seen in a video and was declared dead in 2010.<ref name=\"Bell dead\">{{cite news| last=Taloney| first=Jessica| title=Memorial Service For Contractor Missing In Iraq| url=http://www.wkrg.com/story/21596813/memorial-service-for-contractor-missing-in-iraq| accessdate=July 26, 2013| publisher=[[WKRG-TV]]| date=April 8, 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150522234800/http://www.wkrg.com/story/21596813/memorial-service-for-contractor-missing-in-iraq| archivedate=May 22, 2015}}</ref>\n:* [[Aban Elias]], an Iraqi-American engineer from [[Denver]], was shown being held hostage in a video on May 3, 2004. He has not been seen or heard from since.\n:* Radim Sadeq Mohammed Sadeq, also called \"Dean Sadek\", a businessman kidnapped on November 2, 2004, in Baghdad. He was shown in a video that month and in another video dated Christmas Eve but released in late January. He has not been seen or heard from since. His kidnappers demanded the release of Iraqi prisoners.\n:* Jeffrey Ake, a contractor, was kidnapped on April 11, 2005, and shown in a videotape two days later. He has not been seen or heard from since. His kidnappers demanded $2 million in exchange for his release. After three weeks of negotiations, the kidnappers cut off all communication. Ake is presumed dead and his family held a private funeral for him in the summer of 2014.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/06/06/AR2006060601551_pf.html | work=The Washington Post | title=We Have Your Husband | first=Peter | last=Slevin | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/22/world/middleeast/22missing.html | work=The New York Times | first=Jack | last=Healy | title=With Withdrawal Looming, Trails Grow Cold for Americans Missing in Iraq | date=May 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southbendtribune.com/news/kidnapping-of-laporte-businessman-in-iraq-worth-remembering/article_ba1e60a8-e1d8-11e4-a2ba-dfe7ce9326d6.html?mode=jqm|title=Kidnapping of LaPorte businessman in Iraq worth remembering|work=South Bend Tribune|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Non-coalition ==\n=== Algeria ===\n==== 2 Killed ====\n:* Ali Belaroussi, Algerian [[Charg\u00e9 d'affaires]], and Azzedin Belkadi, Algerian diplomatic attache, were kidnapped on July 21, 2005 in Baghdad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2002395198_iraq22.html|title=Algerian diplomats kidnapped|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> The Algerian government, on July 27, 2005, said the diplomats had been killed.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/22/international/middleeast/22iraq.html | work=The New York Times | title=Gunmen Abduct Algeria's Top Diplomat and a Colleague in Baghdad | first=Edward | last=Wong | date=July 22, 2005 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>http://www.arabnews.com/?page=4&section=0&article=67378&d=23&m=7&y=2005&pix=world.jpg&category=World Arabnews.com</ref>\n\n=== Austria ===\n==== 1 Killed ====\n:* Bert Nussbaumer, a contractor, was kidnapped along with four Americans on November 16, 2006. They appeared in two hostage videos released in December 2006 and January 2007. Their kidnappers demanded the withdrawal of America troops from Iraq and the release of all Iraqi prisoners in exchange for the hostages' release. One of Nussbaumer's fingers was sent to U.S. authorities in February 2008. Three of the Americans and Nussbaumer were found dead in March 2008. The other American was found dead in April 2008.<ref name=\"buffalonews.com\"/>\n\n=== Bangladesh ===\n==== 1 Released ====\n:* Abul Kashem, a truck driver, was kidnapped on October 28, 2004, as he ferried supplies to Kuwait. He was freed on December 10, 2004.<ref name=sasian>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/south_asia/4084895.stm South Asian hostages in Iraq 'freed'] BBC.</ref>\n\n=== Brazil ===\n==== 1 Killed ====\n:* Jo\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 Vasconcelos, an engineer, was kidnapped on January 19, 2005, in an ambush on the [[Route Irish|Baghdad Airport road]]. His body was found more than two years after his kidnapping. It is believed that he died from injuries sustained in the abduction shortly after arriving at the house where his captors planned to hold him.<ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/14/america/LA-GEN-Brazil-Iraq-Missing.php IHT.com]</ref>\n\n=== Canada ===\n====1 Killed ====\n:* Zaid Meerwali, who held dual Canadian-Iraqi citizenship, was seized August 2, 2005, and $250,000 in ransom was demanded. Officials in Canada said, that on August 15, 2005, he had been shot in the head while the family was preparing the ransom money.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/an/story/CTVNews/20050816/Zaid_Meerwali_050815|title=CTV News - Top Stories - Breaking News - Top News Headlines|accessdate=29 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511161901/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/an/story/CTVNews/20050816/Zaid_Meerwali_050815|archivedate=11 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n====6 Released/Escaped ====\n:* Fadi Ihsan Fadel, a Syrian-Canadian employed by the International Rescue Committee, was taken hostage in [[Najaf]] on April 8, 2004 but released on April 16, 2004.\n:* Naji al-Kuwaiti, was taken hostage on April 28, 2004, and released on May 4, 2004.\n:* [[Scott Taylor (journalist)|Scott Taylor]], was a journalist abducted by [[Ansar al-Islam]] in [[Tal Afar]] on September 9, 2004. He was released five days later.\n:* [[James Loney (peace activist)|James Loney]] and [[Harmeet Singh Sooden]], human rights workers with [[Christian Peacemaker Teams]], were kidnapped in Baghdad on November 27, 2005, along with an American and Briton. Their Iraqi driver and Iraqi translator were not taken.<ref name=\"SRB Nov 30\"/> They were released as the result of a coalition military operation on March 23, 2006. See [[2005-2006 Christian Peacemaker hostage crisis]].\n:* Fairuz Yamulky was abducted on September 6, 2004. Her driver and another employee were not taken. Yamulky managed to escape with the help of one of her captors sixteen days later.<ref>[http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/1100305069920_95714269/?hub=Canada CTV.ca]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n====1 Unknown ====\n:* Rifat Mohammed Rifat, an Iraqi-born prison worker, was taken hostage on April 8, 2004. He is still missing.\n\n=== The People's Republic of China ===\n==== 15 Released ====\n:* Seven workers - Xue Yougui, Lin Jinping, Li Guiwu, Li Guiping, Wei Weilong, Chen Xiaojin, and Lin Kongming - were abducted on April 11, 2004 near [[Fallujah]], but were released on April 13, 2004.<ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-04/13/content_322838.htm Seven Chinese kidnapped in Iraq are freed] ''China Daily''.</ref>\n:* Eight unemployed construction workers were kidnapped by a group calling itself \"The Islamic Resistance, al-Numan Brigades\" on January 18, 2005, as they tried to leave the country. They were released four days later. The group included three teenagers.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2005/WORLD/meast/01/22/iraq.china.hostages/ | work=CNN | title=Official: 8 Chinese hostages freed | date=January 23, 2005 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2005-01/22/content_411393.htm Embassy: Eight Chinese hostages in Iraq freed], ''China Daily''.</ref>\n\n=== Cyprus ===\n====1 Released ====\n:* Garabet Jean Jekerjian, a man with dual Lebanese-Cypriot citizenship, was abducted in August 2005. He was released on December 31, 2005 in exchange for $200,000 ransom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.islamonline.com/cgi-bin/news_service/middle_east_full_story.asp?service_id=9631|title=islamonline.com|accessdate=29 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112155815/http://www.islamonline.com/cgi-bin/news_service/middle_east_full_story.asp?service_id=9631|archive-date=2016-01-12|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=2296890 |accessdate=August 15, 2006 |title=Scottish News - the Scotsman }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n=== Egypt ===\n====5 Killed ====\n:* Mohammed Mutawalli, a purported \"Egypt spy\", was beheaded in a video on August 10, 2004.<ref>{{cite news | title= Militants behead 'Egyptian spy' in Iraq|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/08/11/1092102482989.html |date=11 August 2004 |publisher= Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:* Nasser Juma, contractor, kidnapped on August 27, 2004, his body was found in the town of [[Baiji, Iraq]] on 5 September 2004.<ref>{{cite news | title= Iraqi violence flares after lull |url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/09/05/1094322645116.html |date=6 September 2004 |publisher= Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:*Ibrahim Mohammed Ismail, 39, driver, 16 January 2005.<ref>{{cite web | title= Daylight hostage murder posted online|url= https://www.smh.com.au/news/After-Saddam/Daylight-hostage-murder-posted-online/2005/01/24/1106415492365.html| date= 24 January 2005|website= smh.com.au |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Web video shows slaying of Egyptian in Iraq |url=http://www.turkishweekly.net/2005/01/24/news/web-video-shows-slaying-of-egyptian-in-iraq/ |date=24 January 2005 |website=turkishweekly.ne |accessdate=25 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409170555/http://www.turkishweekly.net/2005/01/24/news/web-video-shows-slaying-of-egyptian-in-iraq/ |archivedate=9 April 2016 }}</ref>\n:* [[Ihab al-Sherif]], Egyptian envoy to Iraq, kidnapped in Baghdad on July 3, 2005, and reported killed on July 7, 2005.<ref>{{cite news | title= Captors kill Egypt envoy to Iraq| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/4660909.stm |date=8 July 2005 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:*Ibrahim al-Sayyid al-Hilali, translator, abducted 9 December 2005.<ref>{{cite web | title= Egyptian hostage found dead in Iraq| url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/egyptian-hostage-found-dead-in-iraq-1.1185935| date= 10 December 2005|website= irishtimes.com |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n====16 Released ====\n:* Victor Tawfiq Gerges, truck driver, was kidnapped with Turk Bulent Yanik on 1 June 2004. He was released on 18 June 2004.<ref>{{cite news |last=Elias|first=Diana|title= Ex-Iraq Hostage Says He Relied on Faith |url= https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-95720236.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160505040446/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-95720236.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= 5 May 2016 |date= 22 June 2004 |publisher= AP Online |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:* Alsayeid Mohammed Alsayeid Algarabawi, truck driver, was kidnapped on 6 July 2004. He was released on 19 July 2004.<ref>{{cite news | title=IRAQ EGYPTIAN 2 |url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/Iraq-Egyptian-2/cfbb5ba03fd696af77cfd2f3fc86b533?query=iraq\u00a4t=7&orderBy=Relevance&hits=56&referrer=search&search=/search?query=iraq&allFilters=Baghdad:Locations,Islam:Subject,POOL:Source&allFilters=Baghdad:Locations,Islam:Subject,POOL:Source&productType=IncludedProducts&page=1&b=86b533|date=19 July 2004|publisher= Associated Press |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Truck Bomb Kills Nine inIraq|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,126142,00.html|publisher= Fox News|date=19 July 2004|accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Egyptian hostage has been freed, television report says|url= http://www.nwitimes.com/news/egyptian-hostage-has-been-freed-television-report-says/article_749495f4-56fc-58e8-92a0-2cd0627995d5.html||publisher=nwitimes|date=19 July 2004|accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:* Mohammed Ali Sanad, truck driver, was seized with three Indians and three Kenyans on 22 July 2004. He was released on 1 September 2004.<ref>{{cite news|title= IRAQ HOSTAGES | url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/Iraq-Hostages/d81c3ecf75668027e4e8b43ec311919b?current=4&hits=570&query=MIDDLE | date=1 September 2004 |publisher=Associated Press | accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title= Militants in Iraq free seven truckers|url= http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-09/01/content_370816.htm |date= 1 September 2004 |publisher= China Daily |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:* Mohamed Mamdouh Qutb, diplomat, was seized in Baghdad on 23 July 2004. He was released on 26 July 2004.<ref>{{cite news | title= Militants free 'faithful' Egyptian hostage |url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/africa/militants-free-faithful-egyptian-hostage-218122 |date= 27 July 2004 |publisher= iol.co.za|accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title= Kidnapped Egyptian diplomat freed in Iraq: al-Jazeera|url= http://en.people.cn/200407/27/eng20040727_150896.html |date= 27 July 2004 |publisher= People's Daily Online|accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:* Six employees for [[Iraqna]], the local brand name for Egyptian telecoms giant [[Orascom]], were kidnapped on 24 September 2004, with the first two being released on 28 September 2004.<ref>{{cite news | title= Militants free two Egyptian Hostages|url= http://www.abc.net.au/news/2004-09-28/militants-free-two-egyptian-hostages/559464|date= 28 July 2004| publisher=abc.net.au| accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:* Four engineers, Mohammed al-Saadi, Hussein Ashour, Waleed Ismail and Sayed Shaaban working for Egyptian telecoms giant Orascom were kidnapped in Baghdad on 6 February 2005. They were freed the next day by US forces.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/middle_east/4244971.stm | work=BBC News | title=Egyptian hostages freed in Iraq | date=February 7, 2005 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n:* Nabil Tawfiq Sulieman and Matwali Mohammed Salim, engineers for the firm Unitrak, were abducted on a road west of Baghdad, a video on an Islamic website said on 19 March 2005. They were released a day later.<ref>{{cite web | title= Foreign hostages in Iraq |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news2/background/iraq/hostages.html | date=22 June 2006|website= CBC News Online |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n====1 Unknown ====\n:* Samuel Edward, an engineer working for Iraqna Mobile Company, was kidnapped on September 26, 2005, in Baghdad. His Iraqi driver was left unharmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2005/762/eg6.htm|title=Al-Ahram Weekly - Egypt - Newsreel|author=Weekly_Staff|accessdate=29 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130528224630/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2005/762/eg6.htm|archivedate=28 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\n====4 Released ====\n:* Christian Chesnot and Georges Malbrunot, two reporters, were kidnapped along with their Syrian driver on August 21, 2004. The driver was rescued on November 12. The two journalists were released on December 21. France allegedly paid $15 million in ransom for their release.\n:* Florence Aubenas, a reporter for the daily ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]].'' She disappeared January 5, 2005 but was released with her Iraqi translator, Hussein Hanoun al-Saadi, on June 11. France allegedly paid $10 million in ransom for their release.\n:* Bernard Planche, a water engineer, was kidnapped in [[Mansour]] on December 5, 2005. He was freed on January 7, 2006, when his captors fled the house where they were holding him during a military operation.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/meast/01/08/french.hostage/index.html | work=CNN | title=CNN.com - French hostage freed by military - Jan 8, 2006 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Germany ===\n====4 Released ====\n:* [[Susanne Osthoff]], an [[archaeologist]], was kidnapped along with her Iraqi driver on November 25, 2005, according to the German Foreign Ministry. They were released on December 18, 2005, after Germany allegedly paid the kidnappers $5 million ransom. It is also speculated that Germany released [[Mohammed Ali Hammadi]] in exchange for Osthoff's release.\n:*Thomas Nitzschke and Rene Braeunlich, two engineers, were kidnapped by gunmen near [[Baiji]] on January 24, 2006. They appeared in four videos and their kidnappers demanded that Germany end its cooperation with the Iraqi regime, close its mission in Baghdad, ensure that all German businesses cease dealings there, and the release of all Iraqi prisoners held by US forces. On May 2, 2006, the German government announced the two had been freed. Germany allegedly paid $5 million ransom for their release.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/german-hostages-freed-in-iraq-1.605288 German hostages freed in Iraq] CBC.</ref>\n:*Hannelore Marianne Krause, worked for the Austrian embassy in Baghdad, was kidnapped on February 6, 2007, with her son Sinan in Baghdad. Their kidnappers demanded that Germany withdraw its troops from Afghanistan. She was shown in three videos during her captivity. Hannelore was released on July 11, 2007. Her son's fate is unknown.<ref>[[Der Spiegel#Spiegel Online|Spiegel Online]]: [http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,493734,00.html Hannelore Krause Freed in Iraq, Son Still Being Held], July 11, 2007</ref>\n\n====1 Unknown ====\n:*Sinan Krause, a technician at the Iraqi Foreign Ministry, was kidnapped on February 6, 2007, along with his mother Hannelore, in Baghdad. Their kidnappers demanded that Germany withdraw its troops from Afghanistan. Hannelore was released on July 10, 2007, but Sinan hasn't been seen or heard from since a video was released on September 11, 2007. The video was recorded before Hannelore was released. It showed Sinan saying goodbye to his mother. Their kidnappers issued a final 10-day deadline in the video for Germany to withdraw its troops from Afghanistan. They threatened to slit Sinan's throat if their demand was not met. On April 24, 2008, his father appealed to the captors to release his son. The kidnappers ignored the plea and Sinan's fate is unknown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/NewsDetails.aspx?storyid=215584|title=Gulf Daily News \u00bb World News \u00bb Maliki rivals in unity pledge|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== India ===\n====49 Released ====\n:* Antaryami, Sukhdev Singh, and Tilak Raj were truck drivers seized July 22, 2014, with an Egyptian and three Kenyans. They were released September 1, 2014.<ref name=truck>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-09/01/content_370816.htm \"Militants in Iraq free seven truckers\"]. September 1, 2014. China Daily.</ref>\n:* 46 Indian nurses kidnapped by [[Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIS) in Mosul, Iraq. They were released later on and they confirmed they were looked after very well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/1335092/isis-releases-46-kidnapped-indian-nurses-freed-nurses-say-they-were-treated-well/|title=ISIS Releases 46 Kidnapped Indian Nurses. Freed Nurses Say They Were Treated Well|work=The Inquisitr News|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> Two 2017 [[Indian films]] are based on the incident, ''[[Take Off (2017 film)|Take Off]]''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jayaram|first1=Deepika|title=The trailer of ''Take Off'' is trending now|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/the-trailer-of-take-off-is-trending-now/articleshow/56685942.cms|accessdate=26 February 2017|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|date=27 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Express|last1= Web Desk|title=If you liked Akshay Kumar's ''Airlift'', you will love ''Take Off'' trailer. Watch video|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/malayalam/if-you-liked-akshay-kumars-airlift-you-will-love-take-off-trailer-watch-video-4483878/|accessdate=25 February 2017|publisher=[[The Indian Express]]|date=17 January 2017}}</ref> and ''[[Tiger Zinda Hai]]''.<ref name=\"rediff\">{{cite news|url=https://m.rediff.com/news/report/iraq-isis-how-india-got-the-nurses-back-from-iraq/20140704.htm|title=The real story of Tiger Zinda Hai: How India got 46 nurses back from ISIS|work=[[Rediff.com]]|date=7 November 2017|accessdate=8 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n====39 killed====\nForty Indians \u2014 from Punjab, Himachal Pradesh, Bihar and West Bengal \u2014 went missing in June 2014 after Mosul fell to the Islamic State. In 2015, one of them, Harjit Masih, managed to flee from the clutches of Islamic State and said all other Indians were killed. But the External Affairs Minister Sushma Swaraj refused to buy his claims then. In July last year, she said she would declare the missing persons dead until she had a concrete evidence.\n\nSushma Swaraj had last year informed the Parliament that \"sources who gave the government the confidence of not abandoning the search for the abducted Indians in Iraq include a head of state and a foreign minister of another country.\u201d She had then refused to disclose the identity of the sources, citing \u201cdiplomatic confidentiality.\u201d\n\nOn 20 March 2018, Sushma Swaraj declared in the parliament that Thirty-nine missing Indian workers, who were taken hostage by ISIL in the Iraqi city of Mosul, have been killed. \"I have concrete proof that 39 Indians have been killed,\" Swaraj said about the Indians who were abducted by ISIL in 2014. \"We wanted to give the families closure,\" she said. The physical remains of the Indians will be repatriated by the government in a special aircraft, the minister told parliament.<ref>[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/4-years-after-they-went-missing-govt-confirms-39-indians-killed-in-iraq-by-is/articleshow/63389361.cms m.timesofindia.com]</ref>\n\n=== Indonesia ===\n====4 Released ====\n:*Istiqomah binti Misnad and Casingkem binti Aspin, two female workers of an electricity firm were kidnapped along with six Iraqis and two Lebanese in late September 2004. They appeared in a video broadcast on [[Al Jazeera]] on September 30, 2004. The Islamic Army demanded that Indonesia free [[Abu Bakar Bashir]] in exchange for the release of the two women. Bashir refused to be released for the two Indonesian women and Indonesia also said it would not free him. The Islamic Army also demanded that the Lebanese government withdraw all nationals working in Iraq for the release of the two Lebanese men. The women were released on October 4, 2004. The six Iraqis were freed later that month after they \"repented\" working for the Americans and the two Lebanese were freed for ransom in November, 2004.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/indonesian-hostages-released-in-iraq-1.515492 | work=CBC News | title=Indonesian hostages released in Iraq | date=October 4, 2004}}</ref>\n:*[[Meutya Hafid]], a reporter, and Budiyanto, a cameraman, were kidnapped along with their Jordanian driver on February 15, 2005. They were freed on February 21, 2005.<ref>[http://www.jordanembassyus.org/02232005002.htm Jordanembassyus] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060830210811/http://www.jordanembassyus.org/02232005002.htm |date=2006-08-30 }}</ref>\n\n=== Iran ===\n====7 Released====\n:* Fereidoun Jahani, an Iranian diplomat, was kidnapped near [[Karbala]] on August 4, 2004. He was released on September 27, 2004.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/3694236.stm Kidnapped Iranian diplomat freed BBC</ref>\n:* Six Iranian pilgrims and their Iraqi guide were kidnapped on November 28, 2005. Their Iraqi driver was wounded but was not abducted. The Iraqi guide and two of the Iranian pilgrims (all women) were released a day later. The four male hostages were released on February 10, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tehrantimes.com/Index_view.asp?code=111380|title=Tehran Times}}</ref>\n\n=== Ireland ===\n====1 Killed====\n:* [[Margaret Hassan]], the director of [[CARE International]] -- who held British, Iraqi and Irish citizenship -- was kidnapped in Baghdad on October 19, 2004. Her Iraqi driver and Iraqi unarmed security guard were not taken. She was killed in a video released on November 16, 2004.{{citation needed|date=December 2015}}\n\n====1 Released ====\n:*[[Rory Carroll]], a journalist for the British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'', was abducted on October 19, 2005, in Baghdad and released the next day.\n\n=== Israel ===\n====1 Released====\n:* Nabil Razouk, an [[Israeli Arab]] from [[East Jerusalem]] working for the US company Research Triangle International, was kidnapped April 8, 2004. He was freed on April 22, 2004, after pleas from his family and Palestinians.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/pages/ShArt.jhtml?itemNo=418607 Israeli Arab abducted in Iraq said freed] Haaretz.</ref>\n\n=== Jordan ===\n====2 Released ====\n:* Ibrahim al-Maharmeh, a businessman, was kidnapped in Baghdad on March 5, 2005. He was released on March 8, 2005, after a ransom was paid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/iraq/2005-03-07-insurgents-iraq_x.htm|title=USATODAY.com - Insurgent attacks kill 33, wound dozens around Iraq|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n:*Mahmoud Suleiman Saidat, a driver for the Jordanian embassy in Baghdad, was kidnapped on December 20, 2006. He was later shown on a videotape calling for the release of failed suicide bomber [[Sajida Mubarak Atrous al-Rishawi]]. He was released on February 21, 2007.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/4736768.stm | work=BBC News | title=Baghdad market bombing kills 22 | date=February 21, 2006 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==== 6 Unknown ====\n:* Six Jordanians were kidnapped in May 2005. They appeared in a video that aired on Al-Jazeera on May 6, 2005. They haven't been seen or heard from since.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/archive/2005/05/200841014455727205.html|title=Six Jordanians taken captive in Iraq|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Kenya ===\n==== 3 Released ====\n:* Faiz Khamis Salim, Jalal Mohamed Awadh and Ibrahim Khamis Idd were kidnapped on July 22, 2004, with three Indians and an Egyptian. They were freed September 1, 2004.<ref name=truck/>\n\n====2 Unknown ====\n:* Moses Munyao and George Noballa, engineers from the [[Iraqna]] telephone company, were reported kidnapped after an ambush on January 18, 2006. They were never found.<ref>[http://www.kbc.co.ke/story.asp?ID=34630 KBC.co.ke] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080620114306/http://www.kbc.co.ke/story.asp?ID=34630 |date=2008-06-20 }}</ref>\n\n=== Lebanon ===\n==== 3 Released ====\n:* Mohammed Hamad, was kidnapped when he was seven years old on October 22, 2004, after being lured into a car by his captors while he was walking home from school. His captors told him his father was hurt in a car accident. They also told his father that they would behead his son unless they were paid $150,000. They eventually lowered their demand to $70,000 and then lowered it again to $1,725. The $1,725 ransom was paid and Mohammed was released on October 29, 2004.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/3965923.stm | work=BBC News | title=Boy held hostage in Iraq is freed | date=October 29, 2004 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nctimes.com/articles/2004/10/30/news/nation/17_29_2710_29_04.txt|title=Latest North San Diego County headlines|work=The San Diego Union-Tribune|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n:* Marwan Ibrahim al-Qassar and Mohammed Jawdat Hussein were kidnapped by the Islamic Army in Iraq in late on in September 2004 along with six Iraqis and two Indonesian women. They appeared in a video broadcast on Al-Jazeera on September 30, 2004. The Islamic Army demanded that Indonesia free [[Abu Bakar Bashir]] in exchange for the release of the two women. Bashir refused to be released for the two Indonesian women and Indonesia also said it would not free him. The Islamic Army also demanded that the Lebanese government withdraw all nationals working in Iraq for the release of the two Lebanese men. The Iraqis and the two Indonesian women were freed in October 2004. Marwan and Mohammed were freed in exchange for a ransom in November 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aina.org/news/20041004010259.htm|title=Beirut Warned to Stop Lebanese From Working With U.S. in Iraq|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/Page/document/v4/sub/MarketingPage?user_URL=https://www.theglobeandmail.com%2Fservlet%2Fstory%2FRTGAM.20041105.wleban5%2FBNStory%2FFront%2F&ord=1152681575361&brand=theglobeandmail&force_login=true Theglobeandmail.com]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Morocco ===\n==== 2 Killed ====\n:* Driver Abderrahim Boualam and assistant Abdelkrim El Mouhafidim, both workers at the Moroccan embassy in Baghdad, went missing on October 20, 2005 while driving back from [[Jordan]]. On October 25, 2005, militants claimed their kidnapping. On November 3, 2005, Al Qaeda in Iraq said in an internet statement that it had decided to kill the two hostages. [[Ziad Khalaf Raja al-Karbouly]] later confessed to having arranged the kidnappings. He stated that two Kurds were kidnapped with the Moroccans and were later released.<ref>{{cite news |last= Halaby |first=Jamal | title=Iraqi Gov't Agent Admits al-Qaida Killings | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/05/23/AR2006052301188_pf.html |date= 26 May 2006| publisher= Washington Post | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Nepal ===\n==== 12 Killed ====\n:* Gyanendra Shrestha, Manoj Kumar Thakur, Rajendra Kumar Shrestha, Jit Bahadur Thapa, Budha Kumar Shas, Ramesh Khadka, Mangal Bahadur Limbu, Sanjaya Kumar Thakur, Lalan Sing Koirala, Chhok Bahadur Thapa, Prakash Adhikari, and Bishnu Hari Thapa, were twelve Nepalese taken hostage on August 23, 2004. A video from August 31, 2004, showed the beheading of one and the shooting in the head of the eleven others.<ref>[http://icasualties.org/iraq/contractors.aspx Icasualties.org] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320113321/http://icasualties.org/iraq/contractors.aspx |date=March 20, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==== 1 Released ====\n:* Inus Dewari was kidnapped November 1, 2004, in Baghdad. He was released on November 6, 2004.\n\n=== Palestine ===\n==== 1 Unknown ====\n:* Rami Daas, a 26-year-old Palestinian student, was reported by his family as having been kidnapped on May 9, 2005, by gunmen in the northern city of [[Mosul]]. His fate is unknown.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/iraq/hostages.html Foreign hostages in Iraq] CBC</ref>\n\n=== Pakistan ===\n====2 Killed ====\n:* Azad Hussein Khan, an engineer and Sajjad Naeem, a driver, were kidnapped on July 23, 2004, and killed. Their captors demanded their Kuwaiti company leave Iraq. In a video released on July 29, 2004, their bodies were shown. An Iraqi driver who was held with them was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalaging.org/armedconflict/countryreports/middleeast/iraq/kashmir.htm|title=Two Pakistanis, Iraqi kidnapped|accessdate=29 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210000706/http://www.globalaging.org/armedconflict/countryreports/middleeast/iraq/kashmir.htm|archivedate=10 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/pakistani-hostages-killed-by-militants-554864.html | work=The Independent | location=London | title=Pakistani hostages killed by militants | first=Omar | last=Sinan | date=July 29, 2004 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====13 Released ====\n:* Amjad Hafeez, a driver, was kidnapped on June 25, 2004. He was freed on July 2, 2004.\n:* An embassy worker was abducted on April 25, 2005, but released two weeks later.\n:* Eleven construction workers were kidnapped from their bus near Nasiriyah on August 13, 2005. They were released August 22, 2005.\n\n=== Russia ===\n====4 Killed ====\n:*Fyodor Zaitsev, third secretary of the [[Embassy of Russia in Baghdad|Russian Embassy in Iraq]], and embassy employees Rinat Agliulin, Anatoly Smirnov and Oleg Fyodoseyev were [[Abduction of Russian diplomats in Iraq|abducted after an ambush in Baghdad]] on June 3, 2006. Another employee, Vitaly Titov, was shot and killed. A group claimed to have executed them on June 21, 2006, and a video released on June 25, 2006, confirmed their deaths. The kidnapper group gave 48 hours to the Putin administration to pull out his troops from Chechnya. The bodies of the four diplomats were found in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rosbalt.ru/moscow/2012/04/12/969041.html|title=\u0411\u043e\u0435\u0432\u0438\u043a\u0438 \"\u0410\u043b\u044c-\u041a\u0430\u0438\u0434\u044b\" \u0437\u0430\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u044c\u044e \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044c \u043e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0421\u0412\u0420|work=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0431\u0430\u043b\u0442|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.ria.ru/crime/20120410/172729119.html|title=Remains of Russian Diplomats Killed in Iraq 'Discovered'|author=Sputnik|date=10 April 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n====5 Released ====\n:* Three energy workers, working for the Interenergoservis, were kidnapped April 12, 2004, along with five Ukrainians and a man immediately released, all were released the next day with the insurgents apologizing, noting that they did not realise they were Russian and Ukrainian.<ref name=\"indolink.com\"/>\n:* Andrei Meshcheryakov and Aleksandr Gordiyenko, employees of Interenergoservis, were kidnapped on May 10, 2004, but released on May 17, 2004.\n\n=== Somalia ===\n====1 Released ====\n:* Ali Ahmed Mousa, a truck driver, was taken hostage on July 29, 2004, in order to convince his Kuwaiti employer to withdraw from Iraq. He was released several days later.\n\n=== South Africa ===\n====4 Unknown ====\n:*Johann Enslin (48), Andre Durant (38), Hardus Greeff (43) and Callie Scheepers (48), contractors, the so-called Baghdad Four, were abducted at a bogus roadblock in Baghdad by unidentified men on December 10, 2006, along with five Iraqis. The Iraqis were released two days later. Ten days after the abduction, Andre spoke to his wife briefly in a \"proof of life\" phone call. There were some talks that these four were still alive in May 2010, but since then there has been no word on their fate and their families later had them declared legally dead.<ref>{{cite web |title=The forgotten four: kidnapped in 2006 but families still wait|url=http://civiliancontractors.wordpress.com/tag/south-african-contractors |date= 4 October 2012|publisher=Overseas Civilian Contractors |accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Mali hostage's wife still hopeful after three years and only one call |url=http://www.news24.com/archives/city-press/mali-hostages-wife-still-hopeful-after-three-years-and-only-one-call-20150429|publisher =News24|date=14 December 2014| accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Sri Lanka ===\n====1 Released ====\n:* Dinesh Dharmendran Rajaratnam, a truck driver, was kidnapped on October 28, 2004, while ferrying supplies to Kuwait. He was released on December 10, 2004.<ref name=sasian/>\n\n=== Sudan ===\n====6 Killed ====\n:*Six Sudanese truck drivers were kidnapped by Ansar al-Sunnah in April 2005. The six men were shot dead in a video posted on the Internet.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2005-04-28-iraq-sudan-hostage_x.htm | work=USA Today | title=Militant site depicts video purportedly showing killing of six Sudanese | date=April 28, 2005 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====9 Released ====\n:* Noureddin Zakaria, a translator, was kidnapped on October 30, 2004, in [[Ramadi]]. He was released on November 6, 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corpwatch.org/article.php?id=11653|title=CorpWatch : IRAQ: Titan Translator Released by Kidnappers|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n:*Six Sudanese, including the second secretary at the Sudanese embassy, were abducted in Baghdad on December 23, 2005. They were released on December 31, 2005, after Sudan closed its embassy in Baghdad.<ref>[http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/4A23AB42-5E88-4F45-BF16-D6B71142D2D5.htm English.aljazeera.net] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060103043505/http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/4A23AB42-5E88-4F45-BF16-D6B71142D2D5.htm |date=2006-01-03 }}</ref>\n:* Mohammed Haroun Hamad, a truck driver, was kidnapped along with his colleague Maher Ataya sometime in March 2005. The Islamic Army claimed responsibility in a statement and internet video for the abductions on March 9. The group claimed that a Sharia Council would decide their fates. On April 6, 2005, a second video announced that the Sharia Council decided to release Mohammed and Maher after they \"repented\" working for the Americans.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080510105005/http://dc.indymedia.org/newswire/display/120696/index.php DC.indymedia.org]</ref>\n\n=== Sweden ===\n====1 Released ====\n:* Ulf Hjertstr\u00f6m, an oil broker, was taken hostage on March 25, 2005. He was released on May 30, 2005.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/World/Swedish-hostage-shared-cell-with-Wood/2005/06/22/1119321753895.html | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=Swedish hostage shared cell with Wood | date=June 22, 2005}}</ref>\n\n=== Switzerland ===\n==== 2 Released ====\n:*Two Swiss nationals, a married couple who worked for a [[non-governmental organisation|NGO]], were kidnapped on April 20, 2004, by an unknown group. They were held hostage for 48 hours and released on April 22, 2004, after relatives of the kidnappers from the Obaida tribe promised to pressure [[Yemen]]i authorities. Some reports listed the couple as tourists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20040422/iraq_hostagesfreed_20040422?s_name=&no_ads=|title=CTV News - Top Stories - Breaking News - Top News Headlines|accessdate=29 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511163605/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20040422/iraq_hostagesfreed_20040422?s_name=&no_ads=|archivedate=11 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Syria ===\n==== 1 Released ====\n:* Mohammed al-Joundi, the driver for Christian Chesnot and Georges Malbrunot, was kidnapped on August 21, 2004. He was freed by US troops in [[Fallujah]] on November 12, 2004.\n\n=== Turkey ===\n====4 Killed ====\n:* Durmus Kumdereli, a truck driver, was kidnapped on August 14, 2004. He was having dinner in a restaurant a few miles away from Mosul. He was kidnapped in that restaurant with Mustafa K\u00f6ksal by Abu Musab al-Zarqawi's men. Kumdereli was decapitated on August 17, 2004 by Jama'at al-Tawhid wal-Jihad. Koksal was freed on August 18, 2004.\n:* Dursun Ali Yildirim Tek, a truck driver, was kidnapped on July 23, 2006. Two videos were broadcast on the internet in which his captors demanded the Turkish government end all cooperation with Iraq and that they shut down the company Tek worked for. In the second video, a 72-hour deadline was issued in which Turkey had to give in to the captors' demands or Tek would be executed. He was killed in October after the deadline passed and his body was found near Baghdad's Airport. His body was identified a month and a half later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L13483177.htm|title=Thomson Reuters Foundation|author=Thomson Reuters Foundation|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n:* Murat Yuce, a truck driver, was kidnapped in Iraq along with his colleague Aytullah Gezmen in late July 2004. A video showing [[Abu Ayyub al-Masri]] shooting Yuce in the head was posted on a web site on August 2, 2004. Aytullah was released a month later after he \"repented\" working for the Americans.<ref name=\"usatoday.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/iraq/2004-08-18-iraq-journalist_x.htm | work=USA Today | title=Militants comes to journalist's aid, push for his freedom | date=August 19, 2004 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n:* Maher Kemal, a contractor, was reported beheaded on October 11, 2004.<ref>[https://archive.today/20120907092240/http://www.news24.com/Content/World/Archives/IraqiDossier/1072/e50191d7dad347c7bb5d8aa3e0fbb966/11-10-2004-06-21/More_hostages_beheaded News24.com]</ref>\n\n====6 Released ====\n:* Bulent Yanik, a truck driver, was kidnapped on June 1, 2004 and released on June 18.<ref name=\"hibernium.com\">[http://www.hibernium.com/dsgn/hii/archives/2004/06/victor_tawfiq_gerges_jerges.php \"Victor Tawfiq Gerges (Jerges)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924030027/http://www.hibernium.com/dsgn/hii/archives/2004/06/victor_tawfiq_gerges_jerges.php |date=2015-09-24 }} Hibernium.com</ref>\n:* Abdulkadir Tanrikulu, a businessman, abducted by gunmen from the Bakhan Hotel in Baghdad on January 13, 2005. He was freed on June 29, 2005.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002352783_iraq30.html | work=The Seattle Times | title=Gunmen storm northern Iraq city | first1=Caesar | last1=Ahmed | first2=Raheem | last2=Salman | date=June 30, 2005}}</ref>\n:* Ali Musluoglu, a businessman, was kidnapped in Baghdad on May 19, 2005. He was released on September 20, 2005 in exchange for a $250,000 ransom.<ref>[http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/iraq/?id=14570 Middle-east-online.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051127071532/http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/iraq/?id=14570 |date=2005-11-27 }}</ref>\n:* Aytullah Gezmen, a truck driver, was kidnapped on July 31, 2004, along with his colleague Murat Yuce. Murat was executed on August 16, 2004. Aytullah was released a month later after he \"repented\" working for the Americans.<ref name=\"usatoday.com\"/>\n:* Mustafa K\u00f6ksal, a truck driver, was kidnapped on August 14, 2004, along with his colleague Durmus Kumdereli. Kumdereli was beheaded on August 17, 2004. K\u00f6ksal was freed on August 18, 2004.\n:* Hasan Eskimutlu, a technician, was kidnapped on June 14, 2006, along with his Iraqi translator. His captors sent a video to Aljazeera in which they demanded the Turkish government withdraw its ambassador from Baghdad and that they put pressure on the Iraqi government to free male and female prisoners from U.S and Iraqi prisons. They were freed on August 2, 2006.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/World/Kidnapped-Turk-released-in-Iraq/2006/08/03/1154198232641.html | work=The Sydney Morning Herald | title=Kidnapped Turk released in Iraq | date=August 3, 2006}}</ref>\n\n=== United Arab Emirates ===\n==== 1 Released ====\n:*Naji Rashid al-Nuaimi, the first secretary of the UAE's embassy in Baghdad, was abducted by gunmen on May 16, 2006. His captors demanded that the UAE abandon its presence in Iraq. Nuaimi was freed on May 30, 2006. His Sudanese driver was wounded and later died of his injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticle.asp?xfile=data/theuae/2006/May/theuae_May717.xml&section=theuae|title=Iraqi kidnappers release Emirati diplomat three days after his abduction - Khaleej Times|author=(AP)|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Foreign hostages in Afghanistan]]\n* [[Foreign hostages in Nigeria]]\n* [[Foreign hostages in Somalia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* Usher, Sebastian. \"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/3684324.stm Arabs ambivalent over hostage crisis].\" ''[[BBC]]''. Thursday 23 September 2011.\n{{Terrorist incidents in Iraq during the Second Iraq War and Iraqi insurgency (2011\u2013present)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foreign Hostages In Iraq}}\n[[Category:Foreign hostages in Iraq|*]]\n[[Category:Foreign hostages|Iraq]]\n[[Category:Tactics of the Iraqi insurgency (2003\u20132011)]]\n[[Category:Terrorism in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Kidnappings by Islamists]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{cleanup reorganize|date=June 2017}}\n{{confusing|date=June 2017}}\n{{prose|date=June 2017}}\n{{update|date=June 2017}}\n{{citation style|date=September 2014}}\n}}\n\nMembers of the [[Iraqi insurgency (Iraq War)|Iraqi insurgency]] began taking '''foreign hostages in Iraq''' beginning in April 2004. Since then, in a dramatic instance of Islamist kidnapping they have taken captive more than 200 foreigners and thousands of [[Iraqis]]; among them, dozens of hostages were killed and others rescued or freed. In 2004, executions of captives were often filmed, and many were [[decapitation|beheaded]].<ref name=\"SRB Nov 30\">{{cite news|last=Mathewson|first=Judy|title=U.S. Christian Group Names Captives in Iraq, Blames U.S., U.K.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=apjiZ3TwohoI|publisher=Bloomberg News|accessdate=April 24, 2013|date=November 30, 2005<!-- 11:24 EST-->}}</ref> However, the number of the recorded killings decreased significantly. Many hostages remain missing with no clue as to their whereabouts. The [[United States Department of State]] [[Hostage Working Group]] was organized by the [[U.S. Embassy, Baghdad]], in the summer of 2004 to monitor foreign hostages in Iraq.\n\nThe motives for these kidnappings include:\n* influencing foreign governments with troops in Iraq to withdraw\n* influencing foreign companies with workers in Iraq to leave the country\n* [[ransom]] money\n* discouraging travel to Iraq\n* [[prisoner exchange]]\n\nThe following is a list of known civilian foreign hostages in Iraq.\n{{TOC right|limit=4}}\n\n== Coalition ==\n\n=== Australia ===\n==== 2 Released/Rescued ====\n:* [[John Martinkus]], a journalist for [[SBS Television]], was kidnapped on October 16, 2004. He was released on October 18, 2004, after his captors used [[Google]] to verify his status as a journalist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newmatilda.com/print/629 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115052813/http://newmatilda.com/print/629 |archivedate=2010-01-15 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/3755154.stm | work=BBC News | title=Google 'saved' Australian hostage | date=October 19, 2004 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n:* [[Douglas Wood (engineer)|Douglas Wood]], construction engineer was kidnapped along with two Iraqi business associates on April 30, 2005. The two associates were later killed. Wood was rescued on June 15, 2005 in a raid carried out by the [[Iraqi Army]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/iraqi-family-gets-no-answer-to-asylum-plea/2006/05/28/1148754871340.html | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=Iraqi family gets no answer to asylum plea | date=May 29, 2006 | first=Sarah | last=Smiles}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200506/s1393071.htm |title=ABC.net.au |access-date=2009-11-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515212045/http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200506/s1393071.htm |archive-date=2008-05-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Bulgaria ===\n==== 2 Killed ====\n:* Georgi Lazov and Ivailo Kepov, two truck drivers, were seized on June 29, 2004, near [[Mosul]]. Lazov's beheaded body was found on July 14, 2004; Kepov's on July 22, 2004.<ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-07/23/content_351092.htm Body discovery stokes Iraq hostage tension] ''China Daily'', 2004-07-23</ref>\n\n=== Czech Republic ===\n==== 3 Released ====\n:* Reporter Michal Kubal and cameraman Petr Kl\u00edma, of [[\u010cesk\u00e1 televize|Czech television]] and V\u00edt Pohanka from [[\u010cesk\u00fd rozhlas|Czech Radio]] were kidnapped on April 11, 2004. They were freed April 16, 2004.<ref name=cpj>{{cite web|url=http://cpj.org/reports/2008/04/abducted.php|title=Iraq: Journalists Abducted 2003-09|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Denmark ===\n==== 1 Killed ====\n:* Henrik Frandsen was abducted on April 11, 2004, while working on a sewage project, and found dead the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.breakingnews.ie/archives/2004/0421/world/body-of-missing-dane-found-in-iraq-143819.html|title=Body of missing Dane found in Iraq|work=Breaking News|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Italy ===\n==== 4 Killed ====\n:* [[Fabrizio Quattrocchi]], a security guard captured with three others, was reported killed in a video released on April 14, 2004.\n:* [[Enzo Baldoni]], a reporter taken hostage in August and shown being killed in a video released on August 26, 2004. His Iraqi driver-translator was killed during the abduction.\n:* Salvatore Santoro, a photojournalist, reported kidnapped and killed on December 16, 2004.\n:* Iyad Anwar Wali, an Italian-Iraqi businessman, was reported killed on October 2, 2004.\n\n==== 6 Released ====\n:*Umberto Cupertino, Maurizio Agliana and Salvatore Stefio were captured with security guard Fabrizio Quattrocchi on April 29, 2004. The three were freed June 8, 2004.<ref name=smh>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/06/09/1086460306101.html|title=Iraqi hostages freed 'without bloodshed'|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n:*Simona Pari and Simona Torretta, aid workers for a Bridge to Baghdad, were kidnapped along with two Iraqis on September 7, 2004. They were freed on September 28, 2004. Italy allegedly paid $5 million in ransom for their release.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/iraq/article723364.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=How 45m secretly bought freedom of foreign hostages | first=Daniel | last=McGrory | date=May 22, 2006 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref>\n:*[[Giuliana Sgrena]], a reporter for ''Il Manifesto'', was kidnapped on February 4, 2005. Her Iraqi driver and Iraqi translator managed to escape. When she was released on March 4, 2005, her car was shot at by US troops, and Italian agent [[Nicola Calipari]] was killed. Italy allegedly paid $6 million in ransom for her release.\n\n=== Japan ===\n==== 2 Killed ====\n:* [[Shosei Koda]], a tourist, was confirmed beheaded on October 30, 2004. He had been kidnapped on October 26, 2004 by Zarqawi's group.\n:* [[Akihiko Saito]], a security contractor, was kidnapped after a convoy attack and reported killed on May 28, 2005.\n\n==== 3 Released ====\n:* Soichiro Koriyama, Noriaki Imai, and Nahoko Takato, Japanese citizens were kidnapped on April 8, 2004, but released on April 15, 2004.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/panorama/4627777.stm Noriaki Imai profile] BBC</ref>\n\n=== Macedonia ===\n==== 3 Killed ====\n:* Dalibor Lazarevski, Dragan Markovi\u0107, and Zoran Naskovski, were kidnapped August 21, 2004, near Baghdad. They worked for Soufan Engineering, which caters to the needs of the US military and its private contractors. On October 22, 2004, the Macedonian government confirmed the three had been killed.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/3944711.stm Macedonian Iraq hostages killed] BBC, 22 October 2004.</ref>\n\n==== 2 Released ====\n:* Faruk Ademi and Rasim Ramadani, two contractors working for a cleaning company at [[Basra International Airport]] were abducted on February 16, 2006. They were released on February 20, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.osservatoriobalcani.org/article/articleview/9488/1/407|title=Home - Osservatorio Balcani e Caucaso |author=Osservatorio Balcani e Caucaso|work=[[Osservatorio Balcani e Caucaso]]|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== The Philippines ===\n==== 2 Released ====\n:* Angelo de la Cruz, a truck driver, was taken hostage on July 7, 2004. De la Cruz was released after the Philippines withdrew their 51 troops in the country on July 20, 2004. His Iraqi security guard was killed during the abduction.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200407/s1158208.htm Embassy confirms Filipino hostage's release] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050326182212/http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200407/s1158208.htm |date=2005-03-26 }} ABC News Online.</ref>\n:* Roberto Tarongoy, kidnapped on November 1, 2004. He was released eight months later, on June 22, 2005 after a ransom was paid.<ref>[http://edition.cnn.com/2005/WORLD/asiapcf/06/22/iraq.philippines/index.html Iraq hostage free after 7 months] CNN.</ref>\n\n=== Poland ===\n==== 2 Released ====\n:* Jerzy Kos, a contractor kidnapped on June 1, 2004, was freed in an operation on June 8, 2004.<ref name=smh/>\n:* Teresa Borcz Khalifa, a Polish aid worker, was kidnapped on October 28, 2004. She was freed on November 20, 2004.\n\n=== Romania ===\n==== 3 Released ====\n:* Marie Jeanne Ion, Sorin Dumitru Miscoci, and Ovidiu Ohanesian, journalists, were kidnapped on March 28, 2005 in Baghdad. Their Iraqi-American translator, [[Mohammad Munaf]], also went missing with them. They were released on May 22, 2005. Munaf was accused by the Romanian government of organizing the kidnapping and was arrested.<ref name=cpj/><ref>[https://archive.today/20120910021300/http://www.romaniantimes.at/news/General_News/2009-09-22/3042/Munaf%92s_ten-year_prison_sentence_is_final_ Munaf's ten year prison sentence is final] ''Romanian Times''.</ref>\n\n=== South Korea ===\n==== 1 Killed ====\n:* [[Kim Sun-il]], a translator, was kidnapped on May 30, 2004 by Zarqawi's group. He was beheaded in a video released June 22, 2004.\n\n=== Ukraine ===\n==== 5 Released ====\n:* Five energy workers from Interenergoservis were kidnapped on April 12, 2004, along with 3 Russians and a man immediately released, all were released the next day with the insurgents apologizing, noting that they did not realise they were Russian and Ukrainian.<ref name=\"indolink.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indolink.com/printArticleS.php?id=041304055115|title=INDOlink - Indian Diaspora (NRI) News - Russian, Ukrainian Hostages In Iraq Freed|accessdate=29 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303174651/http://www.indolink.com/printArticleS.php?id=041304055115|archive-date=2016-03-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\n==== 5 Killed ====\n:* [[Kenneth Bigley|Kenneth John Bigley]], a civil engineer, who was kidnapped September 16, 2004. The two Americans kidnapped with him were beheaded and Bigley was beheaded around October 7.\n:* Jason Swindlehurst, Jason Creswell, Alec Maclachlan and Alan McMenemy, four security contractors, were kidnapped with Peter Moore, a computer consultant, on May 29, 2007. Their captors were Shia militiamen who demanded the withdrawal of British troops from Iraq and release of all Iraqi prisoners in exchange for the hostages's release. Creswell, McMenemy and Moore appeared in videos released in November 2007, February 2008 and July 2008. The captors claimed that Swindlehurst killed himself on May 25, 2008. However, that turned out to be a lie. The bodies of Swindlehurst and Creswell were recovered on June 19, 2009. On July 29, 2009, it was revealed that Maclachlan and McMenemy had also been killed. Maclachlan's body was recovered on September 1, 2009. McMenemy's body was recovered on January 20, 2012.<ref>{{cite news | first1=Sean | last1=Rayment | first2=Damien | last2=McElroy |title=British hostages in Iraq named after bodies found|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iraq/5594701/British-hostages-in-Iraq-named-after-bodies-found.html | publisher = Daily Telegraph | location=London | date=June 21, 2009 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"khaleejtimes.com\">[http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticleNew.asp?col=&section=middleeast&xfile=data/middleeast/2009/July/middleeast_July705.xml Khaleejtimes.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608213422/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticleNew.asp?col=&section=middleeast&xfile=data%2Fmiddleeast%2F2009%2FJuly%2Fmiddleeast_July705.xml |date=2011-06-08 }}</ref><ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\">{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/iraq/article6820635.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=End the torment says Brown as death of British hostage is confirmed | first=Oliver | last=August | date=September 4, 2009 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc16660750\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16660750 | work=BBC | title= Body of Iraq kidnap victim Alan McMenemy handed over | date=January 20, 2012 | accessdate=January 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==== 6 Released ====\n:* Gary Teeley, a laundry contractor at an American base outside [[Nasiriyah]], was kidnapped on April 5, 2004. He was freed by his kidnappers on April 11, 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?art_id=qw1081751040494B262|title=Violence rages on in Fallujah despite truce|author=Independent Newspapers Online|work=Independent Online|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n:* [[James Brandon (journalist)|James Brandon]], a freelance journalist for ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'', was kidnapped after 30 masked gunmen stormed into his hotel in [[Basra]] on August 12, 2004. He was freed on August 13, 2004, by his captors.<ref name=cpj/>\n:* Phillip Sands, a freelancer reporter, was abducted on December 26, 2005, along with his Iraqi interpreter and Iraqi driver. His abductors were gunmen who planned on using him to get Britain to pull all troops out of Iraq and release all Iraqi prisoners. Phillip was filmed pleading for his life. However, the tape was never sent to Al Jazeera. On December 31, 2005, Phillip and his two colleagues were rescued by U.S. troops who revealed that no one knew they were missing.<ref name=cpj/>\n:* [[Norman Kember|Norman Frank Kember]], an aid worker for Christian Peacemaker Teams, was kidnapped along with two Canadians and an American on November 27, 2005. Their Iraqi driver and Iraqi translator were not taken.<ref name=\"SRB Nov 30\"/> He was released as the result of a Coalition operation on March 23, 2006. See [[2005-2006 Christian Peacemaker hostage crisis]].\n:* Richard Butler, a journalist working for [[CBS News]], was kidnapped in Basra on February 10, 2008, with his Iraqi interpreter Aqeel Khadhir. The translator was freed on February 13, 2008. Butler was rescued on April 14, 2008 by Iraqi forces.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/15/world/middleeast/15iraq.html | work=The New York Times | title=Two Journalists Are Released in Iraq | first1=Erica | last1=Goode | first2=Qais | last2=Mizher | date=April 15, 2008 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Kidnapped CBS Journalist Freed In Iraq |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/kidnapped-cbs-journalist-freed-in-iraq/ |date= 14 April 2008 |publisher= cbsnews |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:* Peter Moore, a computer consultant, and his four security guards were kidnapped from the Iraqi Finance ministry on May 29, 2007.<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/dec/30/iran-britons-baghdad-kidnapping | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Revealed: hand of Iran behind Britons' Baghdad kidnapping | first=Guy | last=Grandjean | date=December 30, 2009 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref> Peter and two of his security guards appeared in videos released in November 2007, February 2008 and July 2008. Their captors were Shia militiamen who demanded the withdrawal of British troops from Iraq and the release of all Iraqi prisoners in exchange for the hostages's release. Their captors claimed that Swindlehurst killed himself on May 25, 2008. However that turned out to be a lie. The bodies of Swindlehurst and Creswell were recovered on June 19, 2009. Both of them were shot dead. On July 29, 2009, it was revealed that Maclachlan and McMenemy were also killed. The body of Maclachlan was recovered on September 1, 2009. He was also shot dead. McMenemy's body was recovered on January 20, 2012.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iraq/5594701/British-hostages-in-Iraq-named-after-bodies-found.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | title=British hostages in Iraq named after bodies found Two British men, Jason Creswell and Jason Swindlehurst, have been named by the Foreign Office as \"highly likely\" to have been killed, after being kidnapped and held hostage in Iraq since 2007 | first1=Sean | last1=Rayment | first2=Damien | last2=McElroy | date=June 21, 2009 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"khaleejtimes.com\"/><ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"bbc16660750\"/> Moore was released on December 30, 2009 in exchange for the release of [[Qais Khazali]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8435075.stm | work=BBC News | title=UK hostage released alive in Iraq | date=December 30, 2009 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref> In December 2009 evidence uncovered during an investigation by the Guardian newspaper and Guardian Films linked the [[Quds Force]] to the kidnappings of Moore, Swindlehurst, Maclachlan, Creswell and McMenemy.<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\"/>\n\n=== United States ===\n====11 Killed====\n:* [[Nick Berg|Nicholas Evan Berg]], a 26 year old freelancer, went missing on 9 April 2004. His widely publicized beheading was shown in a video on 11 May 2004. His body had been found the day before. [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]] personally beheaded Berg.<ref>''[[Die Welt]] '', 20 November 2014.</ref>\n:* Owen Eugene \"Jack\" Armstrong and Jack Hensley, two contractors for the [[construction]] firm ''Gulf Supplies Commercial Services'' of the [[United Arab Emirates]],<ref name=\"employer\">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/09/20/iraq.beheading/|title=Video shows American hostage beheaded|accessdate=30 March 2008|publisher=CNN|date=20 September 2004}}</ref> were kidnapped along with a Briton named [[Kenneth Bigley|Kenneth John Bigley]] on September 16, 2004. Armstrong was [[decapitation|beheaded]]<ref name=factbox>[https://www.reuters.com/article/topNews/idUSL297059220070531 FACTBOX-Prominent kidnappings of foreigners in Iraq] Accessed 12 March 2008.</ref> on 20 September 2004.<ref name=\"captors\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/american-hostage-beheaded-video-1.473228|title=American hostage beheaded: video|accessdate=2008-03-30|publisher=CBC|date=20 September 2004}}</ref> Abu Musab al-Zarqawi personally beheaded Armstrong.<ref>Romans, Christine and Rhonda Schaffler. \"[http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-13436508_ITM American Beheaded in Iraq; Dates for Presidential Debates to be Set; Dan Rather Apologizes for Bush Story - Part 1]\", accessmylibrary.com, 20 September 2004; retrieved 9 March 2011.</ref> The following day, the group beheaded Hensley, and threatened to kill Bigley, unless the [[United States]] met their demands to free all women prisoners in Iraqi jails.<ref name=\"employer\"/> Bigley was beheaded in October 2004.<ref name=factbox/>\n:* [[Ronald Alan Schulz]], an electrician, was reported kidnapped on 6 December 2005. On 19 December 2005, the Islamic Army released a video showing Schulz's killing in which he is shot in the head after the U.S. refused to release all Iraqi prisoners. His remains were found in September 2008 and confirmed to be Schulz's the next month.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081030/ap_on_re_us/iraq_hostage_burial_1 Re killing of Ronald Schulz], News.yahoo.com; accessed 16 September 2015.</ref>\n:* [[Tom Fox (activist)|Thomas William Fox]], an aid worker working for [[Christian Peacemaker Teams]], was reported kidnapped on November 27, 2005, along with two Canadians and a Briton. Their Iraqi driver and Iraqi translator were not taken.<ref name=\"SRB Nov 30\"/> His body was found in a rubbish heap on 10 March 2006 (see [[2005-2006 Christian Peacemaker hostage crisis]]).\n:*John Roy Young, Joshua Mark Munns, Paul Christopher Reuben and Jonathon Michael Cote, four security contractors, were kidnapped with an Austrian named Bert Nussbaumer on November 16, 2006. They appeared in two hostage videos released in December 2006 and January 2007. The kidnapped contractors stated in their video that they would not be released until the following demands had been made; the withdrawal of American troops from Iraq and the release of all Iraqi prisoners in exchange for the hostages's release. Four fingers were sent to U.S. authorities in February 2008. The fingers belonged to Munns, Reuben, Cote and Nussbaumer. The bodies of Young, Nussbaumer, Munns and Reuben were recovered in March 2008. Cote's body was recovered in April 2008.<ref name=\"buffalonews.com\">[http://www.buffalonews.com/cityregion/story/477265.html Buffalonews.com]</ref><ref>[http://www.buffalonews.com/cityregion/buffaloerie/story/331348.html Buffalonews.com]</ref>\n:*Ronald Withrow, a contractor, was kidnapped along with his translator and driver on 5 January 2007. The translator and driver were found dead the next day. One of Withrow's fingers was sent to U.S. authorities in February 2008. His body was recovered in March 2008.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/28/world/middleeast/28bodies.html 2 More Bodies ID'd as Kidnapped Contractors], nytimes.com; 28 March 2008.</ref>\n:*[[Steven Vincent|Steven Charles Vincent]], a journalist, was kidnapped along with his Iraqi translator, Nouriya Itais Wadi, in Basra on 2 August 2005. They were bound, gagged, taken to an undisclosed location where for five hours they were beaten and interrogated, then taken to the outskirts of town and shot. They were found by British and Iraqi policemen but Vincent was dead, shot in the back at close range. Wadi survived despite having been shot three times.<ref name=cpj/>\n\n==== 6 Released/Escaped ====\n:* [[Jill Carroll]], a freelance reporter for the Boston-based ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'', was kidnapped in West Baghdad on January 7, 2006, by unknown gunmen. Her Iraqi translator was killed during the abduction. Her Iraqi driver escaped. Her kidnappers demanded the release of all female Iraqi prisoners. She was shown in four videos during her captivity. She was released on March 30, 2006.\n:* [[Micah Garen]], a freelance reporter, was kidnapped along with his Iraqi translator, Amir Doushi, on August 13, 2004, near [[Nasiriyah]]. They were freed on August 22, 2004.<ref name=cpj/>\n:* [[Roy Hallums]], an employee of a Saudi trading company, was seized along with Roberto Tarangoy, Inus Dewari and three Iraqi security guards on November 1, 2004, in Baghdad. The three Iraqi security guards were later released. Dewari was released on November 10, 2004. Hallums was shown in a video aired on January 25, 2005. Tarongoy was released on June 22, 2005. On September 7, 2005, Hallums was freed in an operation conducted by [[Delta Force]].\n:* Thomas Hamill, a truck driver, was seized in a deadly convoy attack on April 9, 2004 (see [[2004 Iraq KBR Convoy Ambush]]). He was later shown in a video, but escaped on May 1, 2004.<ref>\"[http://edition.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/05/02/iraq.main/index.html Kidnapped U.S. contractor found safe]\". May 2, 2004, CNN.</ref>\n:* Issa T. Salomi, a civilian contractor, was kidnapped by a Shiite militia group on January 23, 2010, and shown in a video in February 2010. His kidnappers demanded the release of Iraqi prisoners, the withdrawal of all foreign troops from Iraq, the prosecution of security contractors employed by [[Blackwater Worldwide]] and compensation to Iraqi families. He was released on March 25, 2010 in exchange for the release of four Iraqi prisoners.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/02/06/AR2010020601062.html | work=The Washington Post | first1=Ernesto | last1=Londo\u00f1o | first2=Leila | last2=Fadel | title=American contractor kidnapped in Iraq | date=February 6, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/id/36067041|title=Contractor found in Iraq; family rejoices - World news - Mideast/N. Africa - Conflict in Iraq - NBC News|work=NBC News|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n:* [[Paul Taggart]], a freelance photographer, was kidnapped on October 10, 2004. He was released on October 12, 2004.<ref name=cpj/>\n\n==== 5 Unknown ====\n:* [[Kirk von Ackermann]], contractor for a Turkish company, disappeared on October 9, 2003 after leaving a meeting at FOB Pacesetter. His vehicle was found abandoned later that same day.\n:* Timothy Edward Bell, a contractor for [[Halliburton]], went missing on April 9, 2004. He was never seen in a video and was declared dead in 2010.<ref name=\"Bell dead\">{{cite news| last=Taloney| first=Jessica| title=Memorial Service For Contractor Missing In Iraq| url=http://www.wkrg.com/story/21596813/memorial-service-for-contractor-missing-in-iraq| accessdate=July 26, 2013| publisher=[[WKRG-TV]]| date=April 8, 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150522234800/http://www.wkrg.com/story/21596813/memorial-service-for-contractor-missing-in-iraq| archivedate=May 22, 2015}}</ref>\n:* [[Aban Elias]], an Iraqi-American engineer from [[Denver]], was shown being held hostage in a video on May 3, 2004. He has not been seen or heard from since.\n:* Radim Sadeq Mohammed Sadeq, also called \"Dean Sadek\", a businessman kidnapped on November 2, 2004, in Baghdad. He was shown in a video that month and in another video dated Christmas Eve but released in late January. He has not been seen or heard from since. His kidnappers demanded the release of Iraqi prisoners.\n:* Jeffrey Ake, a contractor, was kidnapped on April 11, 2005, and shown in a videotape two days later. He has not been seen or heard from since. His kidnappers demanded $2 million in exchange for his release. After three weeks of negotiations, the kidnappers cut off all communication. Ake is presumed dead and his family held a private funeral for him in the summer of 2014.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/06/06/AR2006060601551_pf.html | work=The Washington Post | title=We Have Your Husband | first=Peter | last=Slevin | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/22/world/middleeast/22missing.html | work=The New York Times | first=Jack | last=Healy | title=With Withdrawal Looming, Trails Grow Cold for Americans Missing in Iraq | date=May 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southbendtribune.com/news/kidnapping-of-laporte-businessman-in-iraq-worth-remembering/article_ba1e60a8-e1d8-11e4-a2ba-dfe7ce9326d6.html?mode=jqm|title=Kidnapping of LaPorte businessman in Iraq worth remembering|work=South Bend Tribune|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Non-coalition ==\n=== Algeria ===\n==== 2 Killed ====\n:* Ali Belaroussi, Algerian [[Charg\u00e9 d'affaires]], and Azzedin Belkadi, Algerian diplomatic attache, were kidnapped on July 21, 2005 in Baghdad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2002395198_iraq22.html|title=Algerian diplomats kidnapped|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> The Algerian government, on July 27, 2005, said the diplomats had been killed.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/22/international/middleeast/22iraq.html | work=The New York Times | title=Gunmen Abduct Algeria's Top Diplomat and a Colleague in Baghdad | first=Edward | last=Wong | date=July 22, 2005 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>http://www.arabnews.com/?page=4&section=0&article=67378&d=23&m=7&y=2005&pix=world.jpg&category=World Arabnews.com</ref>\n\n=== Austria ===\n==== 1 Killed ====\n:* Bert Nussbaumer, a contractor, was kidnapped along with four Americans on November 16, 2006. They appeared in two hostage videos released in December 2006 and January 2007. Their kidnappers demanded the withdrawal of America troops from Iraq and the release of all Iraqi prisoners in exchange for the hostages' release. One of Nussbaumer's fingers was sent to U.S. authorities in February 2008. Three of the Americans and Nussbaumer were found dead in March 2008. The other American was found dead in April 2008.<ref name=\"buffalonews.com\"/>\n\n=== Bangladesh ===\n==== 1 Released ====\n:* Abul Kashem, a truck driver, was kidnapped on October 28, 2004, as he ferried supplies to Kuwait. He was freed on December 10, 2004.<ref name=sasian>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/south_asia/4084895.stm South Asian hostages in Iraq 'freed'] BBC.</ref>\n\n=== Brazil ===\n==== 1 Killed ====\n:* Jo\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 Vasconcelos, an engineer, was kidnapped on January 19, 2005, in an ambush on the [[Route Irish|Baghdad Airport road]]. His body was found more than two years after his kidnapping. It is believed that he died from injuries sustained in the abduction shortly after arriving at the house where his captors planned to hold him.<ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/14/america/LA-GEN-Brazil-Iraq-Missing.php IHT.com]</ref>\n\n=== Canada ===\n====1 Killed ====\n:* Zaid Meerwali, who held dual Canadian-Iraqi citizenship, was seized August 2, 2005, and $250,000 in ransom was demanded. Officials in Canada said, that on August 15, 2005, he had been shot in the head while the family was preparing the ransom money.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/an/story/CTVNews/20050816/Zaid_Meerwali_050815|title=CTV News - Top Stories - Breaking News - Top News Headlines|accessdate=29 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511161901/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/an/story/CTVNews/20050816/Zaid_Meerwali_050815|archivedate=11 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n====6 Released/Escaped ====\n:* Fadi Ihsan Fadel, a Syrian-Canadian employed by the International Rescue Committee, was taken hostage in [[Najaf]] on April 8, 2004 but released on April 16, 2004.\n:* Naji al-Kuwaiti, was taken hostage on April 28, 2004, and released on May 4, 2004.\n:* [[Scott Taylor (journalist)|Scott Taylor]], was a journalist abducted by [[Ansar al-Islam]] in [[Tal Afar]] on September 9, 2004. He was released five days later.\n:* [[James Loney (peace activist)|James Loney]] and [[Harmeet Singh Sooden]], human rights workers with [[Christian Peacemaker Teams]], were kidnapped in Baghdad on November 27, 2005, along with an American and Briton. Their Iraqi driver and Iraqi translator were not taken.<ref name=\"SRB Nov 30\"/> They were released as the result of a coalition military operation on March 23, 2006. See [[2005-2006 Christian Peacemaker hostage crisis]].\n:* Fairuz Yamulky was abducted on September 6, 2004. Her driver and another employee were not taken. Yamulky managed to escape with the help of one of her captors sixteen days later.<ref>[http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/1100305069920_95714269/?hub=Canada CTV.ca]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n====1 Unknown ====\n:* Rifat Mohammed Rifat, an Iraqi-born prison worker, he was taken hostage on April 8, 2004. He is still missing.\n\n=== The People's Republic of China ===\n==== 15 Released ====\n:* Seven workers - Xue Yougui, Lin Jinping, Li Guiwu, Li Guiping, Wei Weilong, Chen Xiaojin, and Lin Kongming - were abducted on April 11, 2004 near [[Fallujah]], but were released on April 13, 2004.<ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-04/13/content_322838.htm Seven Chinese kidnapped in Iraq are freed] ''China Daily''.</ref>\n:* Eight unemployed construction workers were kidnapped by a group calling itself \"The Islamic Resistance, al-Numan Brigades\" on January 18, 2005, as they tried to leave the country. They were released four days later. The group included three teenagers.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2005/WORLD/meast/01/22/iraq.china.hostages/ | work=CNN | title=Official: 8 Chinese hostages freed | date=January 23, 2005 | accessdate=May 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2005-01/22/content_411393.htm Embassy: Eight Chinese hostages in Iraq freed], ''China Daily''.</ref>\n\n=== Cyprus ===\n====1 Released ====\n:* Garabet Jean Jekerjian, a man with dual Lebanese-Cypriot citizenship, was abducted in August 2005. He was released on December 31, 2005 in exchange for $200,000 ransom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.islamonline.com/cgi-bin/news_service/middle_east_full_story.asp?service_id=9631|title=islamonline.com|accessdate=29 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112155815/http://www.islamonline.com/cgi-bin/news_service/middle_east_full_story.asp?service_id=9631|archive-date=2016-01-12|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=2296890 |accessdate=August 15, 2006 |title=Scottish News - the Scotsman }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n=== Egypt ===\n====5 Killed ====\n:* Mohammed Mutawalli, a purported \"Egypt spy\", was beheaded in a video on August 10, 2004.<ref>{{cite news | title= Militants behead 'Egyptian spy' in Iraq|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/08/11/1092102482989.html |date=11 August 2004 |publisher= Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:* Nasser Juma, contractor, kidnapped on August 27, 2004, his body was found in the town of [[Baiji, Iraq]] on 5 September 2004.<ref>{{cite news | title= Iraqi violence flares after lull |url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/09/05/1094322645116.html |date=6 September 2004 |publisher= Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:*Ibrahim Mohammed Ismail, 39, driver, 16 January 2005.<ref>{{cite web | title= Daylight hostage murder posted online|url= https://www.smh.com.au/news/After-Saddam/Daylight-hostage-murder-posted-online/2005/01/24/1106415492365.html| date= 24 January 2005|website= smh.com.au |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Web video shows slaying of Egyptian in Iraq |url=http://www.turkishweekly.net/2005/01/24/news/web-video-shows-slaying-of-egyptian-in-iraq/ |date=24 January 2005 |website=turkishweekly.ne |accessdate=25 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409170555/http://www.turkishweekly.net/2005/01/24/news/web-video-shows-slaying-of-egyptian-in-iraq/ |archivedate=9 April 2016 }}</ref>\n:* [[Ihab al-Sherif]], Egyptian envoy to Iraq, kidnapped in Baghdad on July 3, 2005, and reported killed on July 7, 2005.<ref>{{cite news | title= Captors kill Egypt envoy to Iraq| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/4660909.stm |date=8 July 2005 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:*Ibrahim al-Sayyid al-Hilali, translator, abducted 9 December 2005.<ref>{{cite web | title= Egyptian hostage found dead in Iraq| url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/egyptian-hostage-found-dead-in-iraq-1.1185935| date= 10 December 2005|website= irishtimes.com |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n====16 Released ====\n:* Victor Tawfiq Gerges, truck driver, was kidnapped with Turk Bulent Yanik on 1 June 2004. He was released on 18 June 2004.<ref>{{cite news |last=Elias|first=Diana|title= Ex-Iraq Hostage Says He Relied on Faith |url= https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-95720236.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160505040446/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-95720236.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= 5 May 2016 |date= 22 June 2004 |publisher= AP Online |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref>\n:* Alsayeid Mohammed Alsayeid Algarabawi, truck driver, was kidnapped on 6 July 2004. He was released on 19 July 2004.<ref>{{cite news | title=IRAQ EGYPTIAN 2 |url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/Iraq-Egyptian-2/cfbb5ba03fd696af77cfd2f3fc86b533?query=iraq\u00a4t=7&orderBy=Relevance&hits=56&referrer=search&search=/search?query=iraq&allFilters=Baghdad:Locations,Islam:Subject,POOL:Source&allFilters=Baghdad:Locations,Islam:Subject,POOL:Source&productType=IncludedProducts&page=1&b=86b533|date=19 July 2004|publisher